<section xml:id="section-cayley-hamilton-terminology">

<title>Terminology and notation</title>

<p><dl>

	<li xml:id="definition-cayley-hamilton-nilpotent">
	<title><term>nilpotent matrix</term></title>
	<idx><h>nilpotent</h><h>matrix</h></idx>
	<p>a square matrix powers of which are eventually the zero matrix</p>
	</li>

	<li>
	<title><term>companion matrix (of a monic polynomial)</term></title>
	<idx><h>companion</h><h>matrix</h></idx>
	<idx><h>matrix</h><h>companion</h></idx>
	<p>
	the <m>n \times n</m> matrix
	<me>
		\begin{bmatrix}
			0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp \cdots \amp 0 \amp -a_0 \\
			1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp \cdots \amp 0 \amp -a_1 \\
			0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp \cdots \amp 0 \amp -a_2 \\
			\vdots \amp \vdots \amp \vdots \amp \amp \vdots \amp \vdots \\
			0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp \cdots \amp 1 \amp -a_{n-1}
		\end{bmatrix}
	</me>,
	where <m>n</m> is the degree and <m>a_0,a_1,\dotsc,a_{n-1}</m> the coefficients of the polynomial
	(with coefficient <m>a_j</m> corresponding to power <m>x^j</m>)
	</p>
	</li>

</dl></p>

</section>
